 four hundred in-depth interviews with middle- and working-class men and women residing in and around multiethnic cities-New York City, Rio de Janeiro, and Tel Aviv-to compare the discriminatory experiences of African Americans, black Brazilians, and Arab Palestinian citizens of Israel, as well as Israeli Ethiopian Jews and Mizrahi (Sephardic) Jews. Detailed analysis reveals significant differences in group behavior: Arab Palestinians frequently remain silent due to resignation and cynicism while black Brazilians see more stigmatization by class than by race, and African Americans confront situations with less hesitation than do Ethiopian Jews and Mizrahim, who tend to downplay their exclusion. The authors account for these patterns by considering the extent to which each group is actually a group, the sociohistorical context of intergroup conflict, and the national ideologies and other cultural repertoires that group members rely on.Getting Respect is a rich and daring book that opens many new perspectives into, and sets a new global agenda for, the comparative analysis of race and ethnicity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDiscriminationzBrazil. 0aDiscriminationzIsrael. 0aDiscriminationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aArab Palestinians.  aBlack Brazilians.  aEthiopian Jews.  aMizrahi Jews.  aNew York.  aRio de Janeiro.  aZionism.  aassault on worth.  acultural membership.  acultural repertoires.  adiscrimination.  aethnicity.  aethnoracial exclusion.  aethnoracial group.  agroup boundaries.  agroupness.  amarginalized groups.  arace relations.  arace.  aracial tension.  aracism.  arecognition.  aredistribution.  aself-identification.  asocial psychology.  astigmatization.1 aHerzog, Hanna,